Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Heat a large #frying pan{} over medium heat (no oil!)

Once hot, add the @flaked almonds{15} and cook, stirring regularly, until lightly
toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Watch them like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Transfer the almonds to a #small bowl{} and set aside.

Pop your frying pan back on medium high heat and add a drizzle of @oil{drizzle}.

Once the oil is hot, add the @chicken thigh{210%g}(diced) to the pan and season
with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir fry until golden brown on the outside,
~{4-5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pour the boiling @water{240%ml} for the couscous into a #saucepan{}
and bring to the boil. When boiling, remove from the heat, stir in the
@couscous{120%g} and half the @chicken stock powder{1}. Pop a #lid{} on the pan
and leave to the side for ~{8-10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled, and
thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or
use a #garlic press{}). Thinly slice the @green chilli{1/2}(thinly sliced). Roughly
chop the @dried apricots{40%g}(roughly chopped). Drain and rinse the
@chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}. Once the chicken is browned, add the onion
to the pan with the chicken, stir together and cook until softened,
~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir the @tagine paste{100} and @sugar{1} into the chicken and onion. Add
half the chilli (or less if you don't like heat!) and cook for ~{1%minute}, then
pour in the water and add the remaining @chicken stock powder{1}. Stir in the
chickpeas, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Bring to the boil then reduce the
heat to medium and simmer until the sauce has reduced slightly and the chicken
is cooked, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooked, stir the @baby spinach{40%g} into the sauce a handful at a time
until wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Taste the tagine and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if
you feel it needs it.

Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{} and spoon into bowls. Serve the tagine on
top of the couscous and sprinkle over the flaked almonds and remaining chilli.
Enjoy!